LOVE that this movie actually uses their names: Barbie Skipper Stacie & Chelsea. I don't like it when they use the characters but change the names like in the 12 Dancing Princesses. This one REALLY IS about Barbie & her sisters. It is kind of like a kids version of National Treasure.  This is a movie that we can just sit & enjoy & I don't have to fast forward through any scenes. Highly recommended!

I admit it that my favorite brand of Barbie are the sister sets.  I love the fact that they have the various ages for kids to play with and different looks (i.e. Skipper is a brunette and they have different interests).  So I have heard this movie about 10 times now as it sits in our car for the girls to watch when we are it for more than a quick trip somewhere.  Good story line about giving back which is hard to find some times in kids movies.  Many of the Disney shows for example are starting to show kids some very disrespectful behaviors and making it cool, which is not what I want them to see.  I had another 12-year old that jumped in with us when we were going over to another town for a visit to the movies and she came in mid-way watching it, but it had her attention until we got out of the car.  The two 12-year-olds and the 5-year old were quiet for the hour car ride.

I don't really review Barbie movies, so I will simply say, this is the first one (and I've seen way too many), that I actually enjoyed watching with my daughters. It was cute and not nearly as annoying as some of the other Barbie movies. I agree with the other reviewers that have compared it to The Goonies, perhaps that's why I enjoyed watching it, well that, and there were no princesses in this one!! (even the super heroes Barbie snuck in a princess, as did the Rock camp, etc., ... ).  But my little girls love it and since the Barbie line has never made an overtly offensive film, and seems to draw upon promoting respectable character traits, I allow my daughters to watch, even if it's princesses. .... But seriously, no princesses in this one!!! It's just sisters, adventure, puppies, love, and fun. The best Barbie movie I've ever seen.

I'd give it 4 1/2 stars if the system would let me. Granted it wasn't quite as fun or exciting as Rock'n Royals was, but the movie was colorful and sweet. Barbie and her sisters head to the town of Willows where they grew up to enjoy a summer full of fun and memories. The girls find a map of Willows that lead to a buried treasure that's been hidden time out of mind--one that Barbie, in her childhood used to trail the treasure, but never found. Barbie's younger sisters decide to head out and hunt down the mysterious hidden treasure while Barbie tries to relive her childhood fun times. As she goes on, Barbie learns that Willows isn't the town she remembers, as it's economically in trouble and even her friend, Christy may have to move away. She suddenly realizes that she's been spending all her time chasing memories instead of enjoying her time with her sisters and grandmother. Now with the foursome banded together again, the girls head on out on an adventure that takes them under the town of Willows to a mysterious cave that may just lead to the amazing lost treasure. It's like Barbie meets Indiana Jones as the girls journey under the city pursued by a pair of wicked yet bumbling carnival workers who want the treasure all for themselves. It's adorable and fun and its own right. I recommend it.
